<title>FOAM Build</title>
<h1>Pom-O-Matic</h1>
<p>Solve your Build troubles with Pom-O-Matic!</p>

<h1>Overview</h1>

<p>The FOAM build is a <b>node</b> tool which executes Javascript methods (<b>Tasks</b>) against Project Object Model (<b>POM</b>)(or a more lighthearted acronym expansion: Pom-O-Matic) files.</p>

<p>The build manages <b>options</b> and <b>tasks</b>:</p>
<ul>
  <li><i>tasks</i> - </li>
  <li>options - provide build specific command line arguments that manipulate flags or set environment variables to impact the selection and operation of <b>tasks</b>.</li>
  <li>tasks - methods which act against the source code to generate an application. </li>
</ul>

<p><b>POMs</b> are JSON files which identify source code, application configuration, and build instructions. They are hierarchical and can exist at any level of a code repository.</p>

<p>Presently, there are two types of POMs, or more precisely, two types of POM <b>fields</b></p>
<ol>
  <li><b>Tooling</b> - fields which configure the Build environment itself.
  <p>Fields <b>options</b> and <b>tasks</b> add support for build specific command line options and methods to process the source code.<br/><i>For example</i>, <b>JavaTooling</b> adds <b>options</b> to allow the configuration of the Java target version, and provide command line arguments to control creating a JAR file or start the JVM with JDPA enabled.  And adds <b>tasks</b> for building and starting from JAR file locally or building a TAR file for remote deployment.</p>
  </li>
  <li><b>Build</b> - fields which declare build inputs.
  <p>Such as code and deployment configuration to include.  <br/><i>For example</i>, specifying the models to generate Java from and specifying the configuration to include in a JAR file.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>There are three distinct build <b>phases</b>:</p>
<ol>
  <li><b>Tooling</b> - the build loads Tooling POMs which add <b>options</b> for command line control, and build <b>tasks</b> specific to the type of code generation, compilation, and deployment to be supported.
  </li>
  <li><b>Environment and Registration</b> - the build processes the Build POMs to (1) set environment variable values for <b>options</b> added during the Tooling phase (i.e., Java target release = 21), and (2) register Build POM <b>tasks</b> to be run when same-named Tooling <b>tasks</b> are run (i.e., <b>buildJavaOpts</b> JAVA_OPTS=-Dxyz before the JVM is started).
  <code>
foam.POM({
  ...
  envs: {
    appName: 'foam',
  },
  ...
  tasks: [
    function javacParameters() {
      JAVA_RELEASE = 21;
    },
    function buildJavaOpts() {
      JAVA_OPTS += ` -DGO_HOME=${APP_HOME}`;
    }

  </code>
  </li>
  <li><b>Task</b> - the build processes the command line arguments, for options added during the Tooling phase, and prepares a set of <b>tasks</b> which are then executed.  The <b>tasks</b> themselves, act on the Build POMs.
  </li>
</ol>

<h1>Command Line Arguments</h1>
<p>Both single character (-h) and GNU getopt word style (--help) arguments are supported.<br/>
The GNU args can also be comma seperated <i>For example</i> --cleanAll,all
</p>
<p>execute <b>--help</b> to see all options</p>
<p>execute <b>--usage</b> for command line examles</p>

<h1>Help on Help</h1>
Build usage is generated by the <b>help</b> option and can be invoked in a number of ways:
<code>
$ node foam3/tools/build.js --help
$ node foam3/tools/build.js -h
$ node foam3/tools/build.js -?
</code>
<p>Help output is broken in three sections: options, tasks, environment variables (envs). Help can display just one of the sections by passing an argument to help.<br/>
For example, the following will only output the environment variables.
<code>$ node foam3/tools/build.js --help:envs</code>
</p>
<p>Help can also output the usage or information of a single option, task, or environment variable. <br/>
For example, the following will only output usage of <b>help</b> itself
<code>$node foam3/tools/build.js --help:help</code>
</p>

<h1>Troubleshooting</h1>
<p>CLI argument <b>--show-report</b> will cause the build to output the final value of all <b>options</b> at the point of exit on error, or just before start CORE.</p>

<h1>POMs</h1>
<h2><i>Incomplete</i></h2>
<p>POMs are hierarchical and a POM is responsible for the files in it's directory and child directories which themselves do not contain a POM.</p>
<h2>POM structure</h2>
<h3>Build POMs</h3>
Fields:
<ul>
  <li>name - a non-unique identifier that distinguishes the POM in it's local scope. Used when reporting POM issues.
  <code>
  foam.POM({
    name: 'foam',
    ...
  </code>
  <p>Also used to set APP_NAME. A different APP_NAME can be specified in <b>envs:</b>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>exclude - directories under this POM which should not be processed if they do not contain a POM.</li>
  <li>envs - map of key-values pairs to set build environment variables or options.
  <code>
  foam.POM({
    name: 'foam-full',
    ...
    envs: {
      appName: 'foam'
    },
  </code>
  </li>
  <li>licenses - source code licenses which applies to the source managed by this POM. </li>
  <li>version - major[-minor-revision] string used to distinguish a build.
  <code>
  foam.POM({
    ...
    version: '1.0.0',
  </code>
  </li>
  <li>projects -  (and flags  -   test) </li>
  <li>files - </li>
  <li>javaFiles - </li>
  <li>journalFiles - </li>
  <li>flowDocFiles - (FUTURE) </li>
  <li>tasks - (project defined tasks)</li>
  <li>copy - (build provided tasks)</li>
  <li>Tooling specific - java, javaDependencies, javaFiles (above)</li>
</ul>


<h4>Creating a Build POM Tasks</h4>

<h3>Tooling POMs</h3>
Fields:
<ul>
  <li>name - a non-unique identifier that distinguishes the POM in it's local scope. Used when reporting POM issues.</li>
  <li>envs - environment variables that are internal to the tooling itself. <i>For example</i> a calculated value that many tasks share, or that one task sets-up for another.</li>
  <li>options - defines a property whose value can be manipulated to impact a <b>task</b>.</li>
  <li>tasks - defines a method which acts against the repository. </li>
</ul>


